<a name="agent"></a>
<h3>Using SSH Agent for passwordless authentication:</h3>

<P>SSH agent is a tool that, once started, will pass authentication 
information to hosts on your behalf. This provides a form of single 
sign-on for your session.
</P>

<P> To use SSH Agent, first, ensure you have a public/private key pair setup. See <a href="#keys"> Setting up a public/private key pair </a></P>
<P> After this, simply login to a CS computer and type:</P>
<i><pre>ssh-agent bash</pre></i> or <i><pre>ssh-agent tcsh</pre></i>
<P>This will spawn a new shell within an SSH Agent session. Now type:</P>
<i><pre>ssh-add</pre></i>
<P> You will be prompted for your passphrase. After it is entered, you will 
be able to login to other CS computers without typing your password.  </P>

<P>Example:</P>
<pre>
pupeckd@fang:~><i>ssh-agent bash</i>
[pupeckd@fang ~]$ <i>ssh-add</i>
Enter passphrase for /home/undergrad/pupeckd/.ssh/id_rsa:
Identity added: /home/undergrad/pupeckd/.ssh/id_rsa (/home/undergrad/pupeckd/.ssh/id_rsa)
[pupeckd@fang ~]$ <i>ssh bingo</i>
pupeckd@bingo:~>
</pre>

<P>If you recieve a prompt like:

<pre>
[pupeckd@fang ~]$ ssh bingo
Password: 
</pre> 

Then it is likley you forgot the authorized keys section of <a href="#keys"> Setting up a public/private key pair </a></P>. 


