<a name="keys"></a>
<h3>Setting up a public/private key pair:</h3>
<P>Public/private key pairs provide an alternate means of authentication for ssh and are the basis of 
passwordless, secure connections. </P>

<P>To setup a public/private key pair, first login to a CS computer, then enter:</P>

<i><pre>ssh-keygen -t rsa</pre></i>

<P>Now you will be prompted for a location, You can just hit enter for the default location.<P> 

<P>Next, you will be prompted for a passphrase twice, choose something long, yet easy to remember.<P>

<P>Example:</P>
<pre>
pupeckd@fang:~><i>ssh-keygen -t rsa</i>
Generating public/private rsa key pair.
Enter file in which to save the key (/home/undergrad/pupeckd/.ssh/id_rsa): 
Enter passphrase (empty for no passphrase): 
Enter same passphrase again: 
Your identification has been saved in /home/undergrad/pupeckd/.ssh/id_rsa.
Your public key has been saved in /home/undergrad/pupeckd/.ssh/id_rsa.
The key fingerprint is:
<s>foo</s> pupeckd@fang.cs.sunyit.edu
The key's randomart image is:
<s>bar</s>
pupeckd@fang:~>
</pre>

<P> Lastly, copy the key into your authorized_keys file by typing: </P>

<i><pre> cat ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub >> ~/.ssh/authorized_keys</pre></i>

